The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen — We often hear that the world we know will meet its end, and the usual explanation is ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Roman Club released the seminal book "The Limits to Growth" more than forty years ago, its basic idea has been with us ever since.
But time is not lenient.
The "Limits to Growth" of 1972 warned humanity that catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, since then, we have witnessed financial panics, but not any real shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, resources created by human ingenuity have more than sufficiently met human consumption.
But the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we continue a trend, focusing on misleading solutions to minor issues while neglecting major problems and wise resolutions.
At the beginning of the 1970s, technological optimism faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society plunged into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited public panic about pollution and also sparked the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" said it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were pessimistic.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people worried about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people consume too much.
Even though our genius has won us some time, in the end we will destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than now.
This view still resonates today, although it is profoundly wrong.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that by 2013, the world would have exhausted aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
However, although commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of their levels from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation has replaced mercury in batteries, dental materials, and thermometers, and by the year 2000, mercury consumption had dropped by 98%, with prices falling by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be depleted by 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, reserves of both are higher than in 1970, despite our greatly increased consumption.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves of the United States, cutting prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries increasing 24 times.
"The Limits to Growth" was wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has slowed since the 1960s.
Food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land is currently in use, and there are another 2.7 billion hectares reserved).
The rate of malnutrition has been reduced by more than half, from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not defeated us either.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where we had no particulate air pollution and were all happy farmers, and in the future, heating chimneys would make it impossible for us to breathe. Reality is completely the opposite.
In 1900, the world's population was only 1.5 billion, and nearly 3 million people — one in every 500 — died annually from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, this rate has dropped to one death in every 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths caused by pollution is still higher than that caused by malaria, its mortality rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Nevertheless, the ideas cultivated by "The Limits to Growth" continue to influence the thinking of the public and the elite.
Take recycling, for example; it is usually just a feel-good gesture, costly to the environment and yielding little benefit.
For instance, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The procedures and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, policies driven by fears of overpopulation leading to self-destruction, such as China's family planning policy and India's forced sterilization programs.
Moreover, although pesticides and other pollutants were believed to kill half of humanity, good pesticide regulation has resulted in only 20 deaths annually in the United States, while pesticide use has created a cheaper and more abundant food supply.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — a movement fueled by pesticide panic — would cost the United States an additional $100 billion annually.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland would be needed — an area equal to half of modern-day California.
Rising prices will lead to a decline in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health impacts (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths annually).
Being obsessed with bleak scenarios prevents us from paying attention to the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, and easily curable diseases still cause 15 million deaths annually — equivalent to a quarter of total deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people are lifted out of poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past thirty years, 680 million people in China have been lifted out of poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of poor people by nearly one billion.
This has brought about widespread improvements in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the release of "The Limits to Growth" shows that we need more, not less, growth.
It is estimated that the expansion of trade can bring more than $10 trillion in annual benefits by the end of this century, and the benefits far outweigh the timid "feel-good" policies that stem from spreading fear.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our infinite potential to create a brighter future.
